TY  - JOUR
T1  - Seeking the Institutional Balance of Power: Avoiding the Power of a Balanced View
AU  - Dunbar, Roger L. M.
AU  - Ahlstrom, David
Y1  - 1995/01/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1995.9503272001
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1995.9503272001
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 171
EP  - 192
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article we distinguish the views of insiders and outsiders and develop propositions suggesting how interactions between them may evolve. Two case studies illustrate how these ideas may manifest themselves in practice. By focusing on gaining control of the balance of institutional power instead of exploring alternative perspectives on controversial issues, we continue to create gaps between what insiders do and what outsiders actually want. Resolution of controversial issues requires that insiders and outsiders reorient themselves away from a self-centered, competitive approach in favor of a more cooperative approach in which the shared objective is an understanding of the issues and better solutions for all concerned.
AB  - In this article we distinguish the views of insiders and outsiders and develop propositions suggesting how interactions between them may evolve. Two case studies illustrate how these ideas may manifest themselves in practice. By focusing on gaining control of the balance of institutional power instead of exploring alternative perspectives on controversial issues, we continue to create gaps between what insiders do and what outsiders actually want. Resolution of controversial issues requires that insiders and outsiders reorient themselves away from a self-centered, competitive approach in favor of a more cooperative approach in which the shared objective is an understanding of the issues and better solutions for all concerned.
