TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Agent Morality View of Business Policy
AU  - Quinn, Dennis P.
AU  - Jones, Thomas M.
Y1  - 1995/01/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1995.9503271989
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1995.9503271989
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 22
EP  - 42
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We develop a philosophical perspective on the moral obligations of managers, which we call agent morality, by examining the moral implications of agency theory. Our view is grounded in noninstrumental ethics, which we argue is logically superior to instrumental ethics. We show that the principal-agent model of the firm, once properly considered, requires that managers fashion business policies with reference first to certain moral duties and second to shareholder wealth.
AB  - We develop a philosophical perspective on the moral obligations of managers, which we call agent morality, by examining the moral implications of agency theory. Our view is grounded in noninstrumental ethics, which we argue is logically superior to instrumental ethics. We show that the principal-agent model of the firm, once properly considered, requires that managers fashion business policies with reference first to certain moral duties and second to shareholder wealth.
